WEBVTT

00:20.960 --> 00:21.760
XXXVII.

00:23.480 --> 00:28.660
The manor house of Ferndean was a building of considerable antiquity, moderate size,

00:28.660 --> 00:32.720
and no architectural pretensions, deep buried in a wood.

00:33.220 --> 00:34.680
I had heard of it before.

00:35.340 --> 00:38.980
Mr. Rochester often spoke of it, and sometimes went there.

00:39.480 --> 00:43.460
His father had purchased the estate for the sake of the game-covers.

00:44.000 --> 00:49.080
He would have let the house, but could find no tenant in consequence of its ineligible

00:49.080 --> 00:51.140
and insolubrious site.

00:51.900 --> 00:57.920
Ferndean then remained uninhabited and unfurnished, with the exception of some two or three rooms

00:57.920 --> 01:02.640
fitted up for the accommodation of the squire, when he went there in the season to shoot.

01:03.540 --> 01:09.440
To this house I came, just air dark, on an evening marked by the characteristics of sad

01:09.440 --> 01:14.440
sky, cold gale, and continued small penetrating rain.

01:15.060 --> 01:20.120
The last mile I performed on foot, having dismissed the chaise and driver with the double

01:20.120 --> 01:21.840
remuneration I had promised.

01:22.680 --> 01:27.920
Even when within a very short distance of the manor house you could see nothing of it,

01:28.080 --> 01:31.420
so thick and dark grew the timber of the gloomy wood about it.

01:32.280 --> 01:37.380
Iron gates between granite pillars showed me where to enter, and passing through them

01:37.380 --> 01:41.420
I found myself at once in the twilight of close-ranked trees.

01:42.200 --> 01:48.060
There was a grass-grown track descending the forest aisle, between whore and knotty shafts

01:48.060 --> 01:49.400
and under-branched arches.

01:49.820 --> 01:55.840
I followed it, expecting soon to reach the dwelling, but it stretched on and on.

01:56.120 --> 01:58.000
It wound far and farther.

01:58.500 --> 02:01.120
No sign of habitation or grounds was visible.

02:01.860 --> 02:04.940
I thought I had taken a wrong direction and lost my way.

02:05.480 --> 02:09.700
The darkness of natural, as well as of sylvan desk, gathered over me.

02:10.000 --> 02:12.080
I looked round in search of another road.

02:12.540 --> 02:13.500
There was none.

02:13.500 --> 02:19.920
All was interwoven stem, columnar trunk, dense summer foliage, no opening anywhere.

02:20.760 --> 02:21.600
I proceeded.

02:22.120 --> 02:23.580
At last my way opened.

02:23.860 --> 02:25.140
The trees thinned a little.

02:25.720 --> 02:31.560
Presently I beheld a railing, then the house, scarce by this dim light distinguishable from

02:31.560 --> 02:35.100
the trees, so dank and green were its decaying walls.

02:36.200 --> 02:41.300
Entering a portal fastened only by a latch, I stood amidst a space of enclosed ground,

02:41.300 --> 02:44.320
from which the wood swept away in a semicircle.

02:44.640 --> 02:50.940
There were no flowers, no garden beds, only a broad gravel walk girdling a grass-plot,

02:51.080 --> 02:54.000
and this set in the heavy frame of the forest.

02:54.580 --> 02:57.800
The house presented two pointed gables in its front.

02:58.340 --> 02:59.980
The windows were lattice to narrow.

03:00.540 --> 03:02.340
The front door was narrow, too.

03:02.560 --> 03:04.220
One step led up to it.

03:04.520 --> 03:10.200
The whole looked, as the host of Rochester Arms had said, quite a desolate spot.

03:10.820 --> 03:13.260
It was as still as a church on a weekday.

03:13.660 --> 03:18.180
The pattering rain on the forest leaves was the only sound audible in its vicinage.

03:19.000 --> 03:20.560
Can there be life here?

03:20.680 --> 03:21.280
I asked.

03:22.460 --> 03:26.360
Yes, life of some kind there was, for I heard a movement.

03:26.960 --> 03:32.240
That narrow front door was unclosing, and some shape was about to issue from the grange.

03:33.040 --> 03:34.140
It opened slowly.

03:34.540 --> 03:39.740
A figure came out into the twilight and stood on the step, a man without a hat.

03:40.420 --> 03:43.820
He stretched forth his hand, as if to feel whether it rained.

03:44.640 --> 03:47.000
Dusk as it was, I had recognized him.

03:47.220 --> 03:51.520
It was my master, Edward Fairfax Rochester, and no other.

03:52.580 --> 03:59.480
I stayed my step, almost my breath, and stood to watch him, to examine him, myself unseen,

03:59.880 --> 04:01.480
and, alas, to him invisible.

04:02.260 --> 04:07.500
It was a sudden meeting, and one in which rapture was kept well in check by pain.

04:08.060 --> 04:13.940
I had no difficulty in restraining my voice from exclamation, my step from hasty advance.

04:14.840 --> 04:18.320
His form was of the same strong and stalwart contour as ever.

04:18.740 --> 04:24.300
His port was still erect, his hair was still raven-black, nor were his features altered

04:24.300 --> 04:24.840
or sunk.

04:25.300 --> 04:30.920
Not in one year's space, by any sorrow, could his athletic strength be quelled, or his vigorous

04:30.920 --> 04:32.200
prime blighted.

04:32.640 --> 04:35.400
But in his countenance I saw a change.

04:36.040 --> 04:38.020
That looked desperate and brooding.

04:38.440 --> 04:44.180
That reminded me of some wronged and fettered wild beast or bird, dangerous to approach

04:44.180 --> 04:45.920
in his sullen woe.

04:46.200 --> 04:52.060
The caged eagle, whose gold-ringed eyes cruelty has extinguished, might look as looked that

04:52.060 --> 04:53.120
sightless Samson.

04:54.240 --> 04:58.600
And Reader, you think I feared him in his blind ferocity?

04:58.600 --> 05:00.940
If you do, you little know me.

05:01.400 --> 05:06.240
A soft hope blent with my sorrow that soon I should dare to drop a kiss on that brow

05:06.240 --> 05:10.340
of rock, and on those lips so sternly sealed beneath it.

05:10.640 --> 05:11.660
But not yet.

05:12.180 --> 05:13.880
I would not accost him yet.

05:14.660 --> 05:20.440
He descended the one step, and advanced slowly and gropingly towards the grass-plat.

05:21.100 --> 05:23.120
Where was his daring stride now?

05:23.520 --> 05:27.140
Then he paused, as if he knew not which way to turn.

05:27.660 --> 05:34.660
He lifted his hand, and opened his eyelids, gazed blank, and, with a straining effort,

05:34.740 --> 05:38.360
on the sky, and towards the amphitheatre of trees.

05:39.120 --> 05:41.980
One saw that all to him was a void darkness.

05:42.680 --> 05:48.020
He stretched his right hand, the left arm, the mutilated one, he kept hidden in his bosom.

05:48.500 --> 05:52.760
He seemed to wish, by touch, to gain an idea of what lay around him.

05:52.760 --> 05:57.400
He met but vacancy still, for the trees were some yards off where he stood.

05:58.200 --> 06:02.920
He relinquished the endeavour, folded his arms, and stood quiet and mute in the rain,

06:03.340 --> 06:05.760
now falling fast on his uncovered head.

06:06.520 --> 06:09.440
At this moment John approached him from some quarter.

06:10.720 --> 06:12.580
Will you take my arm, sir?

06:12.780 --> 06:13.380
He said.

06:13.740 --> 06:15.540
There is a heavy shower coming on.

06:16.000 --> 06:17.380
Had you not better go in?

06:18.160 --> 06:20.820
Let me alone, was the answer.

06:21.380 --> 06:23.880
John withdrew, without having observed me.

06:24.460 --> 06:29.440
Mr. Rochester now tried to walk about, vainly, all was too uncertain.

06:30.100 --> 06:34.160
He groped his way back to the house, and, re-entering it, closed the door.

06:35.140 --> 06:36.780
I now drew near and knocked.

06:37.220 --> 06:39.040
John's wife opened the door for me.

06:39.400 --> 06:41.720
Mary, I said, how are you?

06:42.200 --> 06:44.420
She started as if she had seen a ghost.

06:44.480 --> 06:45.580
I calmed her.

06:46.160 --> 06:46.940
To her hurried.

06:46.940 --> 06:50.580
Is it really you, Miss, come at this late hour to this lonely place?

06:51.120 --> 06:55.660
I answered by taking her hand, and then I followed her into the kitchen, where John

06:55.660 --> 06:57.100
now sat by a good fire.

06:57.640 --> 07:02.060
I explained to them, in a few words, that I had heard all which had happened since I

07:02.060 --> 07:05.180
left Thornfield, and that I was come to see Mr. Rochester.

07:05.780 --> 07:10.880
I asked John to go down to the Turnpike house, where I had dismissed the chaise, and bring

07:10.880 --> 07:16.420
my trunk which I had left there, and then, while I removed my bonnet and shawl, I questioned

07:16.420 --> 07:21.360
Mary as to whether I could be accommodated at the manor house for the night, and finding

07:21.360 --> 07:26.380
that arrangements to that effect, though difficult, would not be impossible, I informed

07:26.380 --> 07:27.380
her I should stay.

07:27.860 --> 07:30.220
Just at this moment the parlour bell rang.

07:31.560 --> 07:37.180
When you go in, said I, tell your master that a person wishes to speak to him, but do not

07:37.180 --> 07:37.940
give my name.

07:38.460 --> 07:41.280
I don't think he will see you, she answered.

07:41.420 --> 07:42.780
He refuses everybody.

07:43.440 --> 07:46.420
When she returned, I inquired what he had said.

07:46.920 --> 07:50.400
You are to send in your name and your business, she replied.

07:50.840 --> 07:55.820
She then proceeded to fill a glass with water, and place it on a tray, together with candles.

07:56.480 --> 07:58.100
Is that what he rang for?

07:58.460 --> 07:59.100
I asked.

07:59.660 --> 08:03.480
Yes, he always has candles brought in at dark, though he is blind.

08:04.440 --> 08:06.860
Give the tray to me, I will carry it in.

08:07.580 --> 08:08.980
I took it from her hand.

08:09.300 --> 08:11.220
She pointed me out the parlour door.

08:11.580 --> 08:13.440
The tray shook as I held it.

08:13.760 --> 08:15.420
The water spilt from the glass.

08:16.020 --> 08:18.340
My heart struck my ribs loud and fast.

08:19.440 --> 08:22.260
Mary opened the door for me and shut it behind me.

08:22.520 --> 08:24.220
This parlour looked gloomy.

08:24.740 --> 08:30.480
A neglected handful of fire burnt low in the grate, and leaning over it with his head supported

08:30.480 --> 08:35.300
against the high, old-fashioned mantelpiece, appeared the blind tenant of the room.

08:35.920 --> 08:41.360
His old dog, Pilot, lay on one side, removed out of the way, and coiled up as if afraid

08:41.360 --> 08:43.340
of being inadvertently trodden upon.

08:44.180 --> 08:46.500
Pilot pricked up his ears when I came in.

08:46.760 --> 08:50.720
Then he jumped up with a yelp and a whine, and he bounded towards me.

08:50.980 --> 08:53.540
He almost knocked the tray from my hands.

08:54.220 --> 08:58.560
I set it on the table, then patted him, and said softly, Lie down.

08:59.300 --> 09:05.440
Mr. Rochester turned mechanically to see what the commotion was, but as he saw nothing,

09:06.060 --> 09:08.120
he returned and sighed.

09:08.960 --> 09:11.460
Give me the water, Mary, he said.

09:12.160 --> 09:15.100
I approached him with the now only half-filled glass.

09:15.740 --> 09:17.440
Pilot followed me, still excited.

09:18.300 --> 09:19.480
What is the matter?

09:19.740 --> 09:20.700
he inquired.

09:21.840 --> 09:23.860
Down, Pilot, I again said.

09:24.320 --> 09:27.540
He checked the water on its way to his lips and seemed to listen.

09:28.010 --> 09:30.040
He drank and put the glass down.

09:30.500 --> 09:32.560
This is you, Mary, is it not?

09:33.500 --> 09:35.400
Mary's in the kitchen, I answered.

09:36.420 --> 09:41.480
He put out his hand with a quick gesture, but not seeing where I stood, he did not touch

09:41.480 --> 09:42.040
me.

09:42.700 --> 09:43.460
Who is this?

09:43.520 --> 09:50.520
Who is this? he demanded, trying, as it seemed, to see with those sightless eyes, an availing

09:50.520 --> 09:51.740
and distressing attempt.

09:52.420 --> 09:53.200
Answer me.

09:53.360 --> 09:56.940
Speak again, he ordered, imperiously and aloud.

09:57.640 --> 09:59.940
Will you have a little more water, sir?

10:00.080 --> 10:03.260
I spilt half of what was in the glass, I said.

10:04.100 --> 10:05.140
Who is it?

10:05.340 --> 10:06.220
What is it?

10:06.240 --> 10:06.980
Who speaks?

10:07.880 --> 10:10.960
Pilot knows me, and John and Mary know I am here.

10:11.360 --> 10:13.540
I came only this evening, I answered.

10:14.600 --> 10:17.200
Great God, what delusion has come over me!

10:17.500 --> 10:19.820
What sweet madness has seized me!

10:20.480 --> 10:22.280
No delusion, no madness.

10:22.680 --> 10:27.340
Your mind, sir, is too strong for delusion, your health too sound for frenzy.

10:28.360 --> 10:29.620
And where is the speaker?

10:29.940 --> 10:31.160
Is it only a voice?

10:31.800 --> 10:36.740
Oh, I cannot see, but I must feel, or my heart will stop and my brain burst.

10:37.260 --> 10:42.040
Whatever, whoever you are, be perceptible to the touch, or I cannot live.

10:42.740 --> 10:43.640
He groped.

10:44.000 --> 10:47.500
I arrested his wandering hand and prisoned it in both mine.

10:48.230 --> 10:52.600
Her very fingers, he cried, her small, slight fingers.

10:52.860 --> 10:54.780
If so, there must be more of her.

10:55.220 --> 10:57.500
The muscular hand broke from my custody.

10:58.080 --> 11:03.460
My arm was seized, my shoulder, neck, waist, I was entwined and gathered to him.

11:04.120 --> 11:04.980
Is it Jane?

11:05.360 --> 11:06.380
What is it?

11:06.640 --> 11:08.860
This is her shape, this is her size.

11:09.420 --> 11:11.100
And this is her voice, I added.

11:11.360 --> 11:13.440
She is all here, her heart too.

11:13.940 --> 11:14.960
God bless you, sir.

11:14.960 --> 11:17.260
I am glad to be so near you again.

11:18.340 --> 11:21.300
Jane Eyre, Jane Eyre, was all he said.

11:22.020 --> 11:24.800
My dear master, I answered, I am Jane Eyre.

11:25.040 --> 11:26.140
I have found you out.

11:26.440 --> 11:27.800
I am come back to you.

11:28.600 --> 11:31.820
In truth, in the flesh, my living Jane?

11:32.520 --> 11:35.440
You touch me, sir, you hold me, and fast enough.

11:35.740 --> 11:38.980
I am not like a corpse, nor vacant like Eyre, am I?

11:39.700 --> 11:44.100
My living darling, these are certainly her limbs, and these her features.

11:44.720 --> 11:47.880
But I cannot be so blessed, after all my misery.

11:48.540 --> 11:54.160
It is a dream, such dreams as I have had at night when I have clasped her once more to

11:54.160 --> 12:00.840
my heart as I do now, and kissed her as thus, and felt that she loved me and trusted that

12:00.840 --> 12:02.420
she would not leave me.

12:03.260 --> 12:05.560
Which I never will, sir, from this day.

12:06.660 --> 12:08.660
Never will, says the vision.

12:09.400 --> 12:15.920
But I always woke and found it an empty mockery, and I was desolate and abandoned, my life

12:15.920 --> 12:22.580
dark, lonely, hopeless, my soul a thirst and forbidden to drink, my heart famished and

12:22.580 --> 12:23.580
never to be fed.

12:24.360 --> 12:29.880
Gentle soft dream nestling in my arms now, you will fly too, as your sisters have all

12:29.880 --> 12:33.040
fled before you, but kiss me before you go.

12:33.580 --> 12:34.680
Embrace me, Jane.

12:35.600 --> 12:37.040
There, sir, and there.

12:37.580 --> 12:41.220
I pressed my lips to his once brilliant and now rayless eyes.

12:41.600 --> 12:44.380
I swept his hair from his brow and kissed that, too.

12:45.000 --> 12:47.020
He suddenly seemed to arouse himself.

12:47.880 --> 12:51.520
The conviction of the reality of all this seized him.

12:52.020 --> 12:53.280
Is it you?

12:53.480 --> 12:54.200
Is it, Jane?

12:54.760 --> 12:56.200
You are come back to me, then?

12:56.920 --> 12:57.720
I am.

12:58.320 --> 13:03.580
And you do not lie dead in some ditch under some stream, and you are not a pining outcast

13:03.580 --> 13:04.500
among strangers?

13:05.300 --> 13:08.480
No, sir, I am an independent woman now.

13:09.400 --> 13:10.080
Independent?

13:10.200 --> 13:11.360
What do you mean, Jane?

13:12.280 --> 13:16.700
My uncle in Madeira is dead, and he left me five thousand pounds.

13:17.720 --> 13:21.340
Ah, this is practical, this is real, he cried.

13:21.480 --> 13:23.260
I should never dream that.

13:23.600 --> 13:30.820
Besides, there is that peculiar voice of hers, so animating and piquant, as well as soft.

13:30.820 --> 13:34.560
It cheers my withered heart, it puts life into it.

13:34.900 --> 13:38.680
What, Janet, are you an independent woman, a rich woman?

13:39.500 --> 13:40.660
Quite rich, sir.

13:40.900 --> 13:45.800
If you won't let me live with you, I can build a house of my own, close up to your door,

13:46.020 --> 13:49.860
and you may come and sit in my parlour when you want company of an evening.

13:50.680 --> 13:56.020
But, as you are rich, Jane, you have now, no doubt, friends who will look after you,

13:56.020 --> 14:00.240
and not suffer you to devote yourself to a blind lame-der like me?

14:01.160 --> 14:04.460
I told you I am independent, sir, as well as rich.

14:04.840 --> 14:06.180
I am my own mistress.

14:07.160 --> 14:08.860
And you will stay with me?

14:09.460 --> 14:11.080
Certainly, unless you object.

14:11.480 --> 14:14.200
I will be your neighbour, your nurse, your housekeeper.

14:14.720 --> 14:15.800
I find you lonely.

14:16.140 --> 14:20.940
I will be your companion, to read to you, to walk with you, to sit with you, to wait

14:20.940 --> 14:23.800
on you, to be eyes and hands to you.

14:23.800 --> 14:26.800
Cease to look so melancholy, my dear master.

14:27.200 --> 14:29.940
You shall not be left desolate so long as I live.

14:30.820 --> 14:32.040
He replied not.

14:32.400 --> 14:35.000
He seemed serious, abstracted.

14:35.240 --> 14:36.320
He sighed.

14:36.780 --> 14:38.980
He half opened his lips as if to speak.

14:39.420 --> 14:40.660
He closed them again.

14:41.260 --> 14:43.020
I felt a little embarrassed.

14:43.900 --> 14:51.200
Perhaps I had too rashly overlapped conventionalities, and he, like St. John, saw impropriety in

14:51.200 --> 14:52.520
my inconsiderateness.

14:52.520 --> 14:58.060
I had indeed made my proposal from the idea that he wished, and would ask me to be his

14:58.060 --> 14:58.520
wife.

14:59.500 --> 15:05.000
An expectation, not the less certain because unexpressed, had buoyed me up, that he would

15:05.000 --> 15:06.680
claim me at once as his own.

15:07.120 --> 15:13.300
But no hint to that effect escaping him, and his countenance becoming more overcast, I

15:13.300 --> 15:18.160
suddenly remembered that I might have been all wrong, and was perhaps playing the fool

15:18.800 --> 15:24.640
unwittingly, and I began gently to withdraw myself from his arms, but he eagerly snatched

15:24.640 --> 15:25.420
me closer.

15:25.960 --> 15:28.600
No, no, Jane, you must not go.

15:28.900 --> 15:34.080
No, I have touched you, heard you, felt the comfort of your presence, the sweetness of

15:34.080 --> 15:35.160
your consolation.

15:35.540 --> 15:37.300
I cannot give up these joys.

15:37.600 --> 15:39.480
I have little left in myself.

15:39.740 --> 15:40.880
I must have you.

15:41.320 --> 15:46.520
The world may laugh, may call me absurd, selfish, but it does not signify.

15:46.520 --> 15:48.720
My very soul demands you.

15:48.860 --> 15:52.800
It will be satisfied, or it will take deadly vengeance on its frame.

15:53.980 --> 15:55.800
Well, sir, I will stay with you.

15:55.800 --> 15:57.000
I have said so.

15:57.700 --> 16:02.860
Yes, but you understand one thing by staying with me, and I understand another.

16:03.760 --> 16:09.080
You perhaps could make up your mind to be about my hand and chair, to wait on me as

16:09.080 --> 16:14.320
a kind little nurse, for you have an affectionate heart and a generous spirit which prompt you

16:14.320 --> 16:19.300
to make sacrifices for those you pity, and that ought to suffice for me, no doubt.

16:19.800 --> 16:23.840
I suppose I should now entertain none but fatherly feelings for you.

16:24.140 --> 16:25.200
Do you think so?

16:25.640 --> 16:27.000
Come, tell me.

16:27.900 --> 16:29.580
I will think what you like, sir.

16:29.820 --> 16:33.220
I am content to be only your nurse, if you think it better.

16:34.580 --> 16:36.940
But you cannot always be my nurse, Janet.

16:37.220 --> 16:38.060
You are young.

16:38.220 --> 16:39.700
You must marry one day.

16:40.220 --> 16:42.040
I don't care about being married.

16:42.780 --> 16:44.180
You should care, Janet.

16:44.600 --> 16:50.760
If I were what I once was, I would try to make you care, but a sightless block."

16:50.760 --> 16:53.140
He relapsed again into gloom.

16:53.620 --> 16:57.500
I, on the contrary, became more cheerful, and took fresh courage.

16:58.080 --> 17:03.540
These last words gave me an insight as to where the difficulty lay, and as it was no

17:03.540 --> 17:07.920
difficulty with me, I felt quite relieved from my previous embarrassment.

17:08.420 --> 17:11.120
I resumed a livelier vein of conversation.

17:12.280 --> 17:17.820
"'It is time some one undertook to rehumanize you,' said I, parting his thick and long uncut

17:17.820 --> 17:23.700
locks, for I see you are being metamorphosed into a lion, or something of that sort.

17:24.060 --> 17:28.500
You have a faux air of Nebuchadnezzar in the fields about you.

17:28.660 --> 17:29.540
That is certain.

17:29.980 --> 17:32.020
Your hair reminds me of eagle's feathers.

17:32.400 --> 17:36.040
Whether your nails are grown like bird's claws or not, I have not yet noticed.

17:36.780 --> 17:42.520
On this arm I have neither hand nor nails,' he said, drawing the mutilated limb from his

17:42.520 --> 17:44.660
breast and showing it to me.

17:45.020 --> 17:47.740
"'It is a mere stump, a ghastly sight.

17:47.940 --> 17:50.140
Don't you think so, Jane?'

17:50.140 --> 17:55.860
"'It is a pity to see it, and a pity to see your eyes, and the scar of fire on your forehead,

17:56.340 --> 18:01.940
and the worst of it is, one is in danger of loving you too well for all this and making

18:01.940 --> 18:03.580
too much of you.'

18:04.100 --> 18:09.980
"'I thought you would be revolted, Jane, when you saw my arm and my sickitized vision.'

18:10.780 --> 18:11.700
"'Did you?

18:12.040 --> 18:16.180
Don't tell me so, lest I should say something disparaging to your judgment.

18:17.160 --> 18:22.080
Now let me leave you an instant to make a better fire and have the hearth swept up.

18:22.440 --> 18:24.620
Can you tell when there is a good fire?'

18:25.740 --> 18:29.600
"'Yes, with the right eye I see a glow, a ruddy haze.

18:29.900 --> 18:31.300
And you see the candles?

18:32.040 --> 18:34.780
Very dimly, each is a luminous cloud.

18:35.540 --> 18:36.900
Can you see me?'

18:37.840 --> 18:42.060
"'No, my fairy, but I am only too thankful to hear and feel you.

18:42.580 --> 18:44.420
When do you take supper?'

18:44.420 --> 18:45.900
"'I never take supper.'

18:46.800 --> 18:48.580
"'But you shall have some to-night.

18:48.800 --> 18:49.640
I am hungry.

18:50.000 --> 18:51.500
So are you, I dare say.

18:51.600 --> 18:52.780
Only you forget.'

18:53.640 --> 18:56.700
"'Summoning Mary, I soon had the room in more cheerful order.

18:56.900 --> 19:00.020
I prepared him likewise a comfortable repast.

19:00.020 --> 19:05.320
My spirits were excited, and with pleasure and ease I talked to him during supper and

19:05.320 --> 19:06.660
for a long time after.

19:07.160 --> 19:13.260
There was no harassing restraint, no repressing of glee and vivacity with him, for with him

19:13.260 --> 19:16.600
I was at perfect ease because I knew I suited him.

19:17.100 --> 19:20.780
All I said or did seemed either to console or revive him.

19:21.700 --> 19:22.820
Delightful consciousness!

19:23.380 --> 19:25.800
It brought to life and light my whole nature.

19:25.800 --> 19:30.220
In his presence I thoroughly lived, and he lived in mine.

19:30.880 --> 19:37.180
Blind as he was, smiles played over his face, joy dawned on his forehead, his liniments

19:37.180 --> 19:38.420
softened and warmed.

19:39.860 --> 19:46.280
After supper he began to ask me many questions of where I had been, what I had been doing,

19:46.660 --> 19:51.160
how I had found him out, but I gave him only very partial replies.

19:51.600 --> 19:54.560
It was too late to enter into particulars that night.

19:54.560 --> 20:01.080
Besides, I wished to touch no deep thrilling chord, to open no fresh well of emotion in

20:01.080 --> 20:01.660
his heart.

20:02.240 --> 20:08.780
My sole present aim was to cheer him, cheered as I have said he was, and yet but by fits.

20:09.620 --> 20:15.100
If a moment's silence broke the conversation, he would turn restless, touch me, then say,

20:15.480 --> 20:15.820
Jane.

20:16.740 --> 20:20.580
You are altogether a human being, Jane, you are certain of that.

20:21.560 --> 20:24.120
I conscientiously believe so, Mr. Rochester.

20:25.200 --> 20:30.340
Yet how on this dark and doleful evening could you so suddenly rise on my lone hearth?

20:30.660 --> 20:35.840
I stretched my hand to take a glass of water from a hireling, and it was given me by you.

20:36.320 --> 20:41.700
I asked a question, expecting John's wife to answer me, and your voice spoke at my ear.

20:42.580 --> 20:50.560
Because I had come in in Mary's stead with the tray, and there is enchantment in the

20:50.560 --> 20:55.420
Who can tell what a dark, dreary, hopeless life I have dragged on for months past?

20:56.100 --> 21:02.320
Doing nothing, expecting nothing, merging night and day, feeling but the sensation of

21:02.320 --> 21:07.960
cold when I let the fire go out, of hunger when I forgot to eat, and then a ceaseless

21:07.960 --> 21:13.040
sorrow, and at times a very delirium of desire to hold my Jane again.

21:13.660 --> 21:18.840
Yes, for her restoration I longed, far more than for that of my lost sight.

21:19.400 --> 21:23.440
How can it be that Jane is with me, and says she loves me?

21:23.980 --> 21:26.180
Will she not depart as suddenly as she came?

21:26.760 --> 21:29.220
To-morrow I fear I shall find her no more.

21:30.000 --> 21:35.560
A commonplace practical reply, out of the train of his own disturbed ideas, was, I was sure,

21:36.020 --> 21:38.960
the best and most reassuring for him in this frame of mind.

21:39.340 --> 21:43.860
I passed my finger over his eyebrows, and remarked that they were scorched,

21:44.100 --> 21:48.360
and that I would apply something which should make them grow as broad and black as ever.

21:49.500 --> 21:53.880
Where is the use of doing me good in any way, beneficent spirit,

21:54.360 --> 22:00.040
when at some fatal moment you will again desert me, passing like a shadow, wither and how to

22:00.040 --> 22:04.880
me unknown, and for me remaining afterwards undiscoverable?

22:06.040 --> 22:08.120
Have you a pocket-comb about you, sir?

22:08.920 --> 22:10.200
What for, Jane?

22:10.980 --> 22:16.700
Just to comb out this shaggy black mane, I find you rather alarming when I examine you close at

22:16.700 --> 22:21.900
hand. You talk of my being a fairy, but I am sure you are more like a brownie.

22:22.500 --> 22:23.880
Am I hideous, Jane?

22:24.680 --> 22:27.180
Very, sir. You always were, you know.

22:28.320 --> 22:32.420
The wickedness has not yet been taken out of you wherever you have sojourned.

22:33.460 --> 22:38.680
Yet I have been with good people, far better than you, a hundred times better people,

22:39.160 --> 22:42.480
possessed of ideas and views you never entertained in your life,

22:42.860 --> 22:44.960
quite more refined and exalted.

22:45.920 --> 22:47.680
Who the deuce have you been with?

22:48.740 --> 22:51.840
If you twist in that way, you will make me pull the hair out of your head,

22:52.100 --> 22:55.800
and then I think you will cease to entertain doubts of my substantiality.

22:56.620 --> 22:58.080
Who have you been with, Jane?

22:58.800 --> 23:04.360
You shall not get it out of me to-night, sir. You must wait till to-morrow. To leave my tale

23:04.360 --> 23:09.080
half-toed, will, you know, be a sort of security that I shall appear at your breakfast table to

23:09.080 --> 23:14.820
finish it. By the by, I must mind not to rise on your hearth with only a glass of water, then,

23:14.820 --> 23:18.760
I must bring an egg at the least, to say nothing of fried ham.

23:19.780 --> 23:25.980
You mocking changeling, fairy born in human bread, you make me feel as I have not felt these

23:25.980 --> 23:32.180
twelve months. If Saul could have had you for his David, the evil spirit would have been exercised

23:32.180 --> 23:38.500
without the aid of the harp. There, sir, you are read up and made decent. Now I'll leave you.

23:38.560 --> 23:43.940
I have been travelling these last three days, and I believe I am tired. Good night.

23:44.820 --> 23:49.320
Just one word, Jane. Were there only ladies in the house where you have been?

23:49.820 --> 23:53.800
I laughed and made my escape, still laughing as I ran upstairs.

23:54.320 --> 23:58.960
A good idea, I thought with glee. I see I have the means of fretting him out

23:58.960 --> 24:04.420
of his melancholy for some time to come. Very early the next morning, I heard him

24:04.420 --> 24:10.600
up in a stir, wandering from one room to another. As soon as Mary came down, I heard the question,

24:10.600 --> 24:17.280
Is Miss Eyre here? Then, which room did you put her into? Was it dry? Is she up? Go and ask if

24:17.280 --> 24:23.740
she wants anything, and when she will come down. I came down as soon as I thought there was a

24:23.740 --> 24:28.960
prospect of breakfast. Entering the room very softly, I had a view of him before he discovered

24:28.960 --> 24:34.800
my presence. It was mournful, indeed, to witness the subjugation of that vigorous spirit to a

24:35.560 --> 24:43.420
infirmity. He sat in his chair, still but not at rest, expectant, evidently, the lines of now

24:43.420 --> 24:49.500
habitual sadness marking his strong features. His countenance reminded one of a lamp quenched,

24:49.720 --> 24:54.860
waiting to be relit, and, alas, it was not himself that could now kindle the luster of

24:54.860 --> 25:01.200
animated expression. He was dependent on another for that office. I had meant to be gay and careless,

25:01.200 --> 25:05.140
but the powerlessness of the strong man touched my heart to the quick.

25:05.940 --> 25:08.820
Still, I accosted him with what vivacity I could.

25:09.560 --> 25:15.440
It is a bright sunny morning, sir, I said. The rain is over and gone, and there is a tender shining

25:15.440 --> 25:21.340
after it. You shall have a walk soon. I had waken the glow. His features beamed.

25:22.160 --> 25:29.080
Oh, you are indeed there, my Skylark. Come to me. You are not gone, not vanished. I heard one of

25:29.080 --> 25:35.700
your kind an hour ago, singing high over the wood, but its song had no music for me, any more than

25:35.700 --> 25:42.000
the rising sun had rays. All the melody on earth is concentrated in my Jane's tongue to my ear.

25:42.460 --> 25:48.420
I am glad it is not naturally a silent one. All the sunshine I can feel is in her presence.

25:49.160 --> 25:54.820
The water stood in my eyes to hear this avowal of his dependence, just as if a royal eagle,

25:54.820 --> 25:59.140
chained to a perch, should be forced to entreat a sparrow to become its purveyor.

25:59.840 --> 26:05.360
But I would not be lacrimose. I dashed off the salt drops and busied myself with preparing

26:05.360 --> 26:11.600
breakfast. Most of the morning was spent in the open air. I led him out of the wet and wild wood

26:11.600 --> 26:17.120
into some cheerful fields. I described to him how brilliantly green they were, how the flowers and

26:17.120 --> 26:23.820
hedges looked refreshed, how sparklingly blue was the sky. I sought a seat for him in a hidden and

26:23.820 --> 26:30.800
lovely spot, a dry stump of a tree, nor did I refuse to let him, when seated, place me on his knee.

26:31.300 --> 26:34.720
Why should I, when both he and I were happier nearer than apart?

26:35.600 --> 26:41.360
Pilot lay beside us, all was quiet. He broke out suddenly while clasping me in his arms.

26:42.280 --> 26:48.480
Cruel, cruel deserter! O Jane, what did I feel when I discovered you had fled from Thornfield,

26:48.480 --> 26:54.340
and when I could nowhere find you, and, after examining your apartment, ascertained you had

26:54.340 --> 27:00.460
taken no money, nor anything which could serve as an equivalent? A pearl necklace I had given you lay

27:00.460 --> 27:05.640
untouched in its little casket. Your trunks were left corded and locked as they had been prepared

27:05.640 --> 27:11.740
for the bridal tour. What could my darling do, I asked, left destitute and penniless?

27:12.220 --> 27:15.120
And what did she do? Let me hear now.

27:16.380 --> 27:21.820
Thus urged, I began the narrative of my experience for the last year. I softened

27:21.820 --> 27:26.860
considerably what related to the three days of wandering and starvation, because to have told

27:26.860 --> 27:33.160
him all would have been to inflict unnecessary pain. The little I did say lacerated his faithful

27:33.160 --> 27:39.720
heart deeper than I wished. I should not have left him thus, he said, without any means of making my

27:39.720 --> 27:46.060
way. I should have told him my intention. I should have confided in him he would never have forced me

27:46.060 --> 27:53.160
to be his mistress. Violent as he had seemed in his despair, he, in truth, loved me far too well

27:53.160 --> 27:58.620
and too tenderly to constitute himself my tyrant. He would have given me half his fortune without

27:58.620 --> 28:04.200
demanding so much as a kiss in return, rather than I should have flung myself friendless on the wide

28:04.200 --> 28:09.640
world. I had endured, he was certain, more than I had confessed to him.

28:10.860 --> 28:16.480
Well, whatever my sufferings had been, they were very short, I answered, and then I proceeded to

28:16.480 --> 28:21.320
tell him how I had been received at Morehouse, how I had obtained the office of schoolmistress,

28:21.540 --> 28:28.080
etc. The accession of fortune, the discovery of my relations, followed in due order. Of course,

28:28.280 --> 28:33.400
St. John River's name came in frequently in the progress of my tale. When I had done, that name

28:33.400 --> 28:41.420
was immediately taken up. This St. John, then, is your cousin? Yes. You have spoken of him often.

28:41.700 --> 28:49.140
Did you like him? He was a very good man, sir. I could not help liking him. A good man? Does that

28:49.140 --> 28:56.020
mean a respectable, well-conducted man of fifty? Or what does it mean? St. John was only twenty-nine,

28:56.020 --> 28:56.480
sir.

28:57.340 --> 29:03.260
Jean encore, as the French say. Is he a person of low stature, phlegmatic and plain,

29:03.740 --> 29:08.760
a person whose goodness consists rather in his guiltlessness of vice than in his prowess and

29:08.760 --> 29:15.640
virtue? He is untiringly active. Great and exalted deeds are what he lives to perform.

29:16.560 --> 29:22.520
But his brain, that is probably rather soft, he means well, but you shrug your shoulders to

29:22.520 --> 29:30.280
hear him talk. He talks little, sir. What he does say is ever to the point. His brain is first rate,

29:30.500 --> 29:39.100
I should think not impressible, but vigorous. Is he an able man, then? Truly able. A thoroughly

29:39.100 --> 29:47.020
educated man? St. John is an accomplished and profound scholar. His manners, I think you said,

29:47.020 --> 29:54.620
not to your taste, priggish and parsonic. I never mentioned his manners, but unless I had a very bad

29:54.620 --> 30:02.220
taste, they must suit it. They are polished, calm, and gentlemanlike. His appearance, I forget what

30:02.220 --> 30:07.540
description you gave of his appearance. A sort of raw curate, half strangled with his white neck

30:07.540 --> 30:15.360
cloth, and stilted up on his thick sole high-lows, eh? St. John dresses well. He is a handsome man,

30:15.360 --> 30:24.180
tall, fair with blue eyes, and a Grecian profile. A side, damn him, to me. Did you like him, Jane?

30:25.180 --> 30:32.680
Yes, Mr. Rochester, I liked him. But you asked me that before. I perceived, of course, the drift of

30:32.680 --> 30:40.220
my interlocutor. Jealousy had got hold of him. She stung him. But the sting was salutary. It gave him

30:40.220 --> 30:45.880
from the gnawing fang of melancholy. I would not, therefore, immediately charm the snake.

30:46.820 --> 30:51.420
Perhaps you would rather not sit any longer on my knee, Miss Eyre, was the next somewhat

30:51.420 --> 30:58.760
unexpected observation. Why not, Mr. Rochester? The picture you have just drawn is suggestive

30:58.760 --> 31:05.360
of a rather too overwhelming contrast. Your words have delineated very prettily a graceful Apollo.

31:05.360 --> 31:13.620
He is present to your imagination, tall, fair, blue-eyed, and with a Grecian profile. Your eyes

31:13.620 --> 31:19.340
dwell on a Vulcan, a real blacksmith, brown, broad-shouldered, and blind and lame into the

31:19.340 --> 31:25.440
bargain. I never thought of it before. But you certainly are rather like Vulcan, sir.

31:26.120 --> 31:32.540
Well, you can leave me, ma'am, but before you go. And he retained me by a firmer grasp than ever.

31:33.100 --> 31:38.240
You will be pleased just to answer me a question or two. He paused.

31:39.060 --> 31:43.660
What questions, Mr. Rochester? Then followed this cross-examination.

31:44.800 --> 31:48.400
St. John made you schoolmistress of Morton before he knew you were his cousin?

31:49.300 --> 32:00.760
Yes. You would often see him? He would visit the school sometimes? Daily. He would approve of your

32:00.760 --> 32:07.460
creature? He approved of them, yes. He would discover many things in you he could not have

32:07.460 --> 32:13.760
expected to find. Some of your accomplishments are not ordinary. I don't know about that.

32:14.760 --> 32:19.560
You had a little cottage near the school, you say. Did he ever come there to see you?

32:20.200 --> 32:24.420
Now and then. Of an evening? Once or twice.

32:25.200 --> 32:31.400
A pause. How long did you reside with him and his sisters after the cousinship was discovered?

32:32.260 --> 32:36.880
Five months. Did Rivers spend much time with the ladies of his family?

32:37.920 --> 32:43.520
Yes. The back parlor was both his study and ours. He sat near the window, and we by the table.

32:44.120 --> 32:48.200
Did he study much? A good deal. What?

32:49.740 --> 32:57.060
Hindostani. And what did you do mean time? I learned German at first. Did he teach you?

32:57.880 --> 33:06.020
He did not understand German. Did he teach you nothing? A little Hindostani. Rivers taught you

33:06.020 --> 33:17.880
Hindostani? Yes, sir. And his sisters also? No. Only you? Only me. Did you ask to learn?

33:18.460 --> 33:28.040
No. He wished to teach you? Yes. A second pause. Why did he wish it? Of what use could Hindostani

33:28.040 --> 33:35.960
be to you? He intended me to go with him to India. Ah, here I reached the root of the matter. He

33:35.960 --> 33:43.520
wanted you to marry him. He asked me to marry him. That is a fiction, an impudent invention to vex me.

33:44.080 --> 33:48.820
I beg your pardon. It is the literal truth. He asked me more than once,

33:49.040 --> 33:52.600
and was as stiff about urging his point as ever you could be.

33:54.620 --> 34:01.260
Miss Eyre, I repeat it. You can leave me. How often am I to say the same thing? Why do you remain

34:01.260 --> 34:07.660
pertinaciously perched on my knee when I have given you notice to quit? Because I am comfortable

34:07.660 --> 34:13.700
there. No, Jane, you are not comfortable there, because your heart is not with me. It is with

34:13.700 --> 34:20.400
this cousin, this St. John. Oh, till this moment I thought my little Jane was all mine. I had a

34:20.400 --> 34:25.480
belief she loved me even when she left me. That was an atom of sweet and much bitter.

34:26.080 --> 34:31.960
Long as we have been parted, hot tears as I have wept over our separation, I never thought that

34:31.960 --> 34:39.940
I was mourning her. She was loving another. But it is useless grieving. Jane, leave me. Go and marry

34:39.940 --> 34:47.400
Rivers. Shake me off then, sir. Push me away, for I'll not leave you of my own accord. Jane,

34:47.540 --> 34:54.260
I ever like your tone of voice. It still renews hope. It sounds so truthful. When I hear it,

34:54.380 --> 35:00.740
it carries me back a year. I forget that you have formed a new tie. But I am not a fool. Go.

35:01.360 --> 35:06.300
Where must I go, sir? Your own way with the husband you have chosen.

35:07.240 --> 35:14.340
Who is that? You know this St. John Rivers. He is not my husband, nor ever will be.

35:14.760 --> 35:22.060
He does not love me. I do not love him. He loves as he can love, and that is not as you love.

35:22.560 --> 35:28.480
A beautiful young lady called Rosamond. He wanted to marry me only because he thought I should make

35:28.480 --> 35:35.600
a suitable missionary's wife, which she would not have done. He is good and great, but severe,

35:35.860 --> 35:42.600
and for me cold as an iceberg. He is not like you, sir. I am not happy at his side, nor near him,

35:42.640 --> 35:49.320
nor with him. He has no indulgence for me, no fondness. He sees nothing attractive in me,

35:49.520 --> 35:55.720
not even youth, only a few useful mental points. Then I must leave you, sir, to go to him?

35:56.360 --> 36:00.540
I shuddered involuntarily and clung instinctively closer to my blind,

36:00.940 --> 36:03.460
but beloved master. He smiled.

36:04.440 --> 36:09.620
What, Jane? Is this true? Is such really the state of matters between you and Rivers?

36:10.520 --> 36:16.260
Absolutely, sir. Oh, you need not be jealous. I wanted to tease you a little to make you less

36:16.260 --> 36:21.200
sad. I thought anger would be better than grief. But if you wished me to love you,

36:21.200 --> 36:25.820
could you but see how much I do love you, you would be proud and content.

36:26.800 --> 36:31.840
All my heart is yours, sir. It belongs to you, and with you it would remain,

36:32.080 --> 36:35.280
were fate to exile the rest of me from your presence for ever.

36:36.660 --> 36:41.060
Again, as he kissed me, painful thoughts darkened his aspect.

36:41.800 --> 36:46.020
My seared vision, my crippled strength, he murmured regretfully.

36:46.660 --> 36:50.680
I caressed in order to soothe him. I knew of what he was thinking,

36:50.800 --> 36:55.740
and wanted to speak for him, but dared not. As he turned aside his face a minute,

36:56.220 --> 37:02.580
I saw a tear slide from under the sealed eyelid, and trickle down the manly cheek. My heart swelled.

37:03.520 --> 37:07.840
I am no better than the old lightning-struck chestnut tree in Thornfield Orchard,

37:08.380 --> 37:12.200
he remarked ere long. And what right would that ruin have

37:12.200 --> 37:15.800
to bid a budding woodbine cover its decay with freshness?

37:17.020 --> 37:23.440
You are no ruin, sir, no lightning-struck tree. You are green and vigorous. Plants will grow

37:23.440 --> 37:27.660
about your roots whether you ask them or not, because they take delight in your bountiful

37:27.660 --> 37:32.420
shadow. And as they grow, they will lean towards you, and wind round you,

37:32.580 --> 37:38.860
because your strength offers them so safe a prop. Again he smiled. I gave him comfort.

37:39.660 --> 37:43.000
You speak of friends, Jane? He asked.

37:43.700 --> 37:48.700
Yes, of friends, I answered rather hesitatingly, for I knew I meant more than friends,

37:48.920 --> 37:52.580
but could not tell what other word to employ. He helped me.

37:53.380 --> 37:55.720
Ah, Jane, but I want a wife.

37:56.540 --> 37:57.320
Do you, sir?

37:58.300 --> 38:00.120
Yes. Is it news to you?

38:00.880 --> 38:03.400
Of course. You said nothing about it before.

38:04.480 --> 38:06.000
Is it unwelcome news?

38:06.700 --> 38:10.600
That depends on circumstances, sir. On your choice.

38:11.640 --> 38:15.460
Which you shall make for me, Jane. I will abide by your decision.

38:17.040 --> 38:19.720
Choose, then, sir, her who loves you best.

38:20.900 --> 38:25.900
I will at least choose her I love best. Jane, will you marry me?

38:26.920 --> 38:27.720
Yes, sir.

38:28.540 --> 38:32.440
A poor blind man, whom you will have to lead about by the hand?

38:33.240 --> 38:34.420
Yes, sir.

38:35.100 --> 38:39.160
A crippled man, twenty years older than you, whom you will have to wait on?

38:39.900 --> 38:41.080
Yes, sir.

38:41.980 --> 38:42.720
Truly, Jane.

38:43.580 --> 38:44.880
Most truly, sir.

38:45.560 --> 38:48.520
Oh, my darling, God bless and reward you.

38:49.200 --> 38:54.860
Mr. Rochester, if ever I did a good deed in my life, if ever I thought a good thought,

38:55.260 --> 39:01.020
if ever I prayed a sincere and blameless prayer, if ever I wished a righteous wish,

39:01.020 --> 39:08.440
I am rewarded now. To be your wife is, for me, to be as happy as I can be on earth.

39:09.280 --> 39:11.300
Because you delight in sacrifice.

39:12.760 --> 39:18.360
Sacrifice? What do I sacrifice? Famine for food, expectation for content?

39:18.920 --> 39:24.220
To be privileged to put my arms round what I value, to press my lips to what I love,

39:24.220 --> 39:31.680
to repose on what I trust, is that to make a sacrifice? If so, then certainly I delight in

39:31.680 --> 39:37.660
sacrifice. And to bear with my infirmities, Jane, to overlook my deficiencies.

39:38.460 --> 39:44.180
Which are none, sir, to me. I love you better now, when I can be really useful to you,

39:44.200 --> 39:49.300
than I did in your state of proud independence, when you disdained every part but that of the

39:49.300 --> 39:57.320
giver and protector. Hitherto I have hated to be helped, to be led. Henceforth I feel I shall

39:57.320 --> 40:03.360
hate it no more. I did not like to put my hand into a hireling's, but it is pleasant to feel

40:03.360 --> 40:09.460
it circled by Jane's little fingers. I preferred utter loneliness to the constant attendance of

40:09.460 --> 40:16.940
servants. But Jane's soft ministry will be a perpetual joy. Jane suits me. Do I suit her?

40:17.740 --> 40:25.060
To the finest fiber of my nature, sir. The case being so, we have nothing in the world to wait for.

40:25.400 --> 40:32.180
We must be married instantly. He looked and spoke with eagerness. His old impetuosity was rising.

40:34.160 --> 40:39.660
We must become one flesh without any delay, Jane. There is but the license to get. Then we marry.

40:40.640 --> 40:44.980
Mr. Rochester, I have just discovered the sun has far declined from its meridian,

40:44.980 --> 40:49.620
and Pilate has actually gone home to his dinner. Let me look at your watch.

40:50.800 --> 40:55.520
Fasten it into your girdle, Janet, and keep it henceforward. I have no use for it.

40:56.160 --> 40:59.880
It is nearly four o'clock in the afternoon, sir. Don't you feel hungry?

41:00.780 --> 41:05.880
The third day from this must be our wedding day, Jane. Never mind fine clothes and jewels now.

41:06.120 --> 41:12.100
All that is not worth a filip. The sun has dried up all the raindrops, sir. The breeze is still.

41:12.100 --> 41:17.400
It is quite hot. Do you know, Jane, I have your little pearl necklace at this moment

41:17.400 --> 41:23.640
fastened round my bronze scrag under my cravat? I have worn it since the day I lost my only treasure,

41:23.980 --> 41:29.500
as a memento of her. We will go home through the wood. That will be the shadiest way.

41:30.120 --> 41:32.600
He pursued his own thoughts without heeding me.

41:33.600 --> 41:42.080
Jane, you think me, I dare say, an irreligious dog, but my heart swells with gratitude to the

41:42.080 --> 41:48.920
man. He sees not as man sees, but far clearer. Judges not as man judges, but far more wisely.

41:49.620 --> 41:56.260
I did wrong. I would have sullied my innocent flower. Breathe guilt on its purity. The

41:56.260 --> 42:02.780
omnipotent snatched it from me. I, in my stiff-necked rebellion, almost cursed the dispensation.

42:03.440 --> 42:08.800
Instead of bending to the decree, I defied it. Divine justice pursued its course.

42:09.400 --> 42:14.820
Disasters came thick on me. I was forced to pass through the valley of the shadow of death.

42:15.740 --> 42:22.100
His chastisements are mighty, and one smote me which has humbled me forever. You know I was proud

42:22.100 --> 42:27.180
of my strength, but what is it now when I must give it over to foreign guidance as a child does

42:27.180 --> 42:35.680
its weakness? Of late, Jane, only, only of late, I began to see and acknowledge the hand of God in

42:35.680 --> 42:43.780
my doom. I began to experience remorse, repentance, the wish for reconcilement to my Maker. I began

42:43.780 --> 42:52.180
sometimes to pray. Very brief prayers they were, but very sincere. Some days since—nay, I can

42:52.180 --> 42:59.880
number them—four. It was last Monday night. A singular mood came over me, one in which grief

42:59.880 --> 43:06.740
replaced frenzy, sorrow sullenness. I had long had the impression that since I could nowhere

43:06.740 --> 43:14.280
find you, you must be dead. Late that night, perhaps it might be between eleven and twelve o'clock,

43:14.660 --> 43:22.340
ere I retired to my dreary rest, I supplicated God that, if it seemed good to him, I might soon

43:22.340 --> 43:28.180
be taken from this life, and admitted to that world to come, where there was still hope of rejoining

43:28.180 --> 43:36.120
Jane. I was in my own room, and sitting by the window, which was open, it soothed me to feel the

43:36.120 --> 43:42.820
balmy night air, though I could see no stars, and only by a vague luminous haze knew the presence

43:42.820 --> 43:51.060
of a moon. I longed for thee, Janet. Oh, I longed for thee both with soul and flesh. I asked of God

43:51.060 --> 43:57.200
at once in anguish and humility if I had not been long enough desolate, afflicted, tormented.

43:57.980 --> 44:04.900
And might not soon taste bliss and peace once more. That I merited all I endured, I acknowledged.

44:05.640 --> 44:11.840
That I could scarcely endure more, I pleaded, and the alpha and omega of my heart's wishes

44:11.840 --> 44:20.880
broken voluntarily from my lips in the words, Jane, Jane, Jane. Did you speak these words aloud?

44:21.740 --> 44:28.680
I did, Jane. If any listener had heard me, he would have thought me mad. I pronounced them with such

44:28.680 --> 44:36.780
frantic energy. And it was last Monday night? Somewhere near midnight? Yes, but the time is of

44:36.780 --> 44:43.560
no consequence. What followed is the strange point. You will think me superstitious. Some

44:43.560 --> 44:50.100
superstition I have in my blood, and always had. Nevertheless, this is true. True, at least, it is

44:50.100 --> 44:58.520
that I heard what I now relate. As I exclaimed, Jane, Jane, Jane, a voice, I cannot tell whence

44:58.520 --> 45:07.000
the voice came, but I know whose voice it was, replied, I am coming. Wait for me. And a moment

45:07.000 --> 45:14.500
after went whispering on the wind the words, Where are you? I'll tell you, if I can, the idea,

45:14.500 --> 45:21.160
the pictures these words open to my mind, yet it is difficult to express what I want to express.

45:21.840 --> 45:27.440
Verndene is buried, as you see, in a heavy wood where sound falls dull and dies unreverberating.

45:28.340 --> 45:34.720
Where are you? seemed spoken amongst mountains, for I heard a hill-sun echo repeat the words.

45:35.580 --> 45:38.920
Cooler and fresher at the moment the gales seemed to visit my brow.

45:39.640 --> 45:46.060
I could have deemed that in some wild, lone scene I and Jane were meeting. In spirit,

45:46.360 --> 45:51.680
I believe we must have met. You no doubt were at that hour in unconscious sleep, Jane.

45:52.240 --> 45:55.240
Perhaps your soul wandered from its cell to comfort mine,

45:55.560 --> 45:59.020
for those were your accents, as certain as I lived they were yours.

46:00.780 --> 46:07.380
Reader, it was on Monday night, near midnight, that I too had received the mysterious summons.

46:07.380 --> 46:13.700
Those were the very words by which I replied to it. I listened to Mr. Rochester's narrative,

46:14.300 --> 46:21.880
but made no disclosure in return. The coincidence struck me as too awful and inexplicable to be

46:21.880 --> 46:28.040
communicated or discussed. If I told anything, my tale would be such as must necessarily make

46:28.040 --> 46:34.740
a profound impression on the mind of my hearer. And that mind, yet from its sufferings too prone

46:34.740 --> 46:40.680
to gloom, needed not the deeper shade of the supernatural. I kept these things then,

46:40.900 --> 46:46.780
and pondered them in my heart. You cannot now wonder, continued my master,

46:47.280 --> 46:53.420
that when you rose upon me so unexpectedly last night, I had difficulty in believing you any

46:53.420 --> 46:58.280
other than a mere voice and vision, something that would melt to silence and annihilation,

46:58.280 --> 47:03.700
as the midnight whisper and mountain echo had melted before. Now I thank God,

47:04.020 --> 47:12.420
I knew it to be otherwise. Yes, I thank God. He put me off his knee, rose, and reverently lifting

47:12.420 --> 47:17.700
his hat from his brow, and bending his sightless eyes to the earth, he stood in mute devotion.

47:18.520 --> 47:24.580
Only the last words of the worship were audible. I thank my Maker, that in the midst of judgment

47:25.220 --> 47:31.400
he has remembered mercy. I humbly entreat my Redeemer to give me strength to lead henceforth

47:31.400 --> 47:38.260
a purer life than I have done hitherto. Then he stretched his hand out to be led. I took

47:38.260 --> 47:44.280
that dear hand, held it a moment to my lips, then let it pass round my shoulder. Being so much

47:44.280 --> 47:50.480
lower of stature than he, I served both for his prop and guide. We entered the wood and wended

47:50.480 --> 47:54.320
homeward. End of chapter 37

